<pre class="bz_comment_text">As I understand it, the original format of the key file was just plain text passwords. It was later extended to parse strings longer than 20 characters as HEX-encoded values to better suit SHA1 and stronger hash functions. ntpkeygen generates two sets of 128-bit keys, using both formats. The latter would be recommended for everyone, but some people might still be putting manually written passwords there. I don't know.

Only AES keys require padding. The older types like MD5, SHA1, SHA256 are ok with any key length.

</pre>
